1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,620
Now that we've examined the print function,

2

00:00:02,620  -->  00:00:04,380
let's expand on this a bit.

3

00:00:04,380  -->  00:00:08,060
While the print function allows us to write a message to the console.

4

00:00:08,060  -->  00:00:11,680
There are two additional keyword parameters we can pass into it,

5

00:00:11,680  -->  00:00:14,480
called sep and end.

6

00:00:14,480  -->  00:00:19,640
The sep parameter specifies the separator between multiple arguments,

7

00:00:19,640  -->  00:00:23,430
and the end operator specifies what to print at the end.

8

00:00:23,430  -->  00:00:27,020
When we think about parameters for a function class or method,

9

00:00:27,020  -->  00:00:31,680
think of them as settings that we can use to customize the behavior of a certain action.

10

00:00:31,680  -->  00:00:33,920
Settings can either be required,

11

00:00:33,920  -->  00:00:37,620
meaning that you must specify what that settings is

12

00:00:37,620  -->  00:00:41,400
value is or an error will occur or optional,

13

00:00:41,400  -->  00:00:45,380
meaning that there will be a default value utilized,

14

00:00:45,380  -->  00:00:49,440
but that can be overwritten by a custom value U pass in.

15

00:00:49,440  -->  00:00:53,335
Think of it like ordering food at a fast food restaurant.

16

00:00:53,335  -->  00:00:55,750
When you order a number one,

17

00:00:55,750  -->  00:00:57,990
maybe that comes with a burger,

18

00:00:57,990  -->  00:00:59,750
fries and a drink.

19

00:00:59,750  -->  00:01:02,670
If you don't customize any of these inputs,

20

00:01:02,670  -->  00:01:05,350
these three items will come with their defaults.

21

00:01:05,350  -->  00:01:07,890
Perhaps a plain burger with ketchup,

22

00:01:07,890  -->  00:01:10,285
small fries and a la soda.

23

00:01:10,285  -->  00:01:13,390
But let's say that there is an optional value to upgrade

24

00:01:13,390  -->  00:01:16,990
your meal to a number five for only $5 more.

25

00:01:16,990  -->  00:01:22,890
The meals upgrade could be an optional parameter to either make the meal bigger,

26

00:01:22,890  -->  00:01:26,670
it's included, or the meal stays the same.

27

00:01:26,670  -->  00:01:30,655
It's not included, and the default is, don't upgrade.

28

00:01:30,655  -->  00:01:34,970
When we think about the SEP and end, keyword parameters.

29

00:01:34,970  -->  00:01:38,410
Let's take a look at an example of this inaction.

30

00:01:38,410  -->  00:01:43,050
If we want to bring multiple elements together with a custom separator,

31

00:01:43,050  -->  00:01:44,610
such as two strings.

32

00:01:44,610  -->  00:01:47,825
This is what we would do. We'll say print,

33

00:01:47,825  -->  00:01:51,250
Hello, and this will be our first item.

34

00:01:51,250  -->  00:01:53,410
World, will be our second item.

35

00:01:53,410  -->  00:01:56,050
We'll declare our sep keyword parameter,

36

00:01:56,050  -->  00:01:58,650
and we're going to put this in quote,

37

00:01:58,650  -->  00:02:03,570
and we're going to put a comma in there and then a space. We'll do another comma.

38

00:02:03,570  -->  00:02:07,270
We'll say end, and then we'll add a exclamation point,

39

00:02:07,270  -->  00:02:08,855
and then we'll close this out.

40

00:02:08,855  -->  00:02:11,840
Can you guess what this will print? It prints?

41

00:02:11,840  -->  00:02:14,365
Hello, comma world, exclamation point.

42

00:02:14,365  -->  00:02:18,060
What is happening is we have multiple inputs as strings,

43

00:02:18,060  -->  00:02:19,940
the hello and world,

44

00:02:19,940  -->  00:02:25,660
and we use a sep parameter right here of comma space

45

00:02:25,660  -->  00:02:29,120
to unite together both of those strings into

46

00:02:29,120  -->  00:02:32,820
one single string with that defined character.

47

00:02:32,820  -->  00:02:34,420
Then the end parameter,

48

00:02:34,420  -->  00:02:37,820
which is to add an exclamation point to the end of the string.

49

00:02:37,820  -->  00:02:40,720
Instead of needing to write a function to do all of this logic,

50

00:02:40,720  -->  00:02:43,360
we can leverage the built in functionality of

51

00:02:43,360  -->  00:02:48,080
these optional parameters in our print statements. How cool is that?
